    <div>
    <h1>South Africa!</h1>
<p>Is South Africa safe for solo female travellers? Although the general feeling is that only the brave venture here on their own, South Africa should be on the favourite destinations list. Not only is it safe to travel to South Africa (within the limits of common sense applicable to any other countries), but it is also one of the best places for solo female travellers due to the variety of things to do. However, it is not recommended for first-time solo travellers. If this is the case, it is preferable to join a group tour instead. From cosmopolitan cities such as Cape Town, wine routes, historical sites, to unforgettable safari experiences, e.g. Mpumalanga and Kruger National Park, there is something to do for everyone. South Africa is the sixth world’s megadiverse countries, home to a large variety of wild animals.  </p>
    <main>
        <h2>What To See</h2>
<p>Here are the top five places to visit in South Africa:</p>
<p><strong>1. Cape Town -</strong> The city is the most vibrant and cosmopolitan part in the African continent. Cape Town is a fantastic destination for solo female travellers. It is perfect for shopping, wine sampling, walks, hiking and boat rides across spectacular scenery. Then there is Bo Kaap, a collection of brightly coloured houses that keep their doors open and you can smell the delicious Cape Malay food. And, if you love penguins (who doesn’t?), you can walk and even swim with them on Boulders Beach. </p>
<p><strong>2.	KwaZulu-Natal -</strong>This province reflects what South Africa stands for: wildlife, mountains, beaches, and approachable local culture. The industrial hub of Durban is home to a potent mixture of cultural backgrounds. Go to Hluhluwe-iMfolozi Park to see both white and black rhinos, a unique experience, rare in the world. </p>
<p><strong>3. Mpumalanga -</strong> East from Gauteng to Mozambique and Swaziland, this province is also named the ‘the land of the rising sun’ and one of the best destinations for wildlife safaris. Experience this epic journey in an open vehicle conducted by well-informed rangers. </p>
<p><strong>4. The Winelands -</strong> This region is all about eating, drinking and relaxation, and the towns still echo the Dutch colonial heritage. Stellenbosch, Paarl, Franschhoek and Somerset West are captivating for their natural attractions. Paarl, the third-oldest town in South Africa, that was visited by Charles Darwin in 1836, is overlooked by the Taal Monument, an Afrikaans icon.</p>
<p><strong>5. The Garden Route -</strong> Holding the legendary status of South Africa’s paradise, this coastal plain stretches between Mossel Bay and Storms River Mouth. Forests, hills and swimming beaches provide great outdoor adventures such as hiking, marine safaris and tubing along the river valley. </p>
</div>

