<div>
<h2>Food</h2>
<p>One of the extras when travelling to a new country is that you can experience the local cuisine prepared with local produce. Most South Africa’s hotels and guesthouses offer a British style cuisine. For those that want to immerse into the local culture further, here is a list of the best-known foods in South Africa to try out:</p>
<p><strong>1. Braais -</strong>Central to their national identity, this meat grill is also a social event and probably the only time to see a South African man cooking. Huge steaks, lamb cutlets and boerewors (farmer’s sausage) accompanied by aluminium foil wrapped vegetables are the traditional barbeque ingredients. Family and friends gather by the fire and serve gallons of beer. </p>
<p><strong>2. Potjiekos and boerekos  -</strong> Butter and sugar rich stews prepared in pots, these foods are made of meat and vegetables cooked indoors or outside on a log fire. </p>
<p><strong>3. Cape Malay  -</strong> Mild, semi-sweet curries, found mostly in Cape Town. This cooking style has been brought to South Africa by Asian and Madagascan slaves, and presents strong Indonesian influences.  </p>
<p><strong>4. Bunny Chow -</strong> Cheap takeaway consisting of a hollow half-loaf of white bread filled with curried beans, chicken, or sardines. </p>
<p><strong>5. Malva -</strong> Rich pudding made of milk, sugar, cream, and apricot jam.  </p>
</div>

