<div>
<h2>Transport</h2>
<p>Getting around in South Africa is easy only in some parts of the country. Therefore, advance research can save a lot of trouble and give you more confidence while you are there. </p>
<p>Public Transport: Several companies run busses in the country, including Greyhound, Intercape, and Baz Bus. Baz Bus caters mainly backpackers, so a great way to meet fellow travellers and they serve the popular routes between major cities or tourist attractions. Greyhound and Intercape busses are suitable for longer journeys, are comfortable and are filled with local people. Train travel is comfortable and safe, and the prices are the lower than any other transportation means.</p>
<p>Cars: Car rental in South Africa is cheap, and although driving here holds a bad reputation, with necessary precautions risks are significantly reduced.</p> 
<p>Taxis: A great option for short distance trips, especially at night when it is not advised to travel alone. </p>
<p>Planes: Flying within South Africa is a suitable option to travel. The prices are comparable to the bus tickets and even last-minute flights on major routes stay unchanged.</p>
</div>

<div>
<h2>Where To Stay</h2>
<p>Accommodation in South Africa varies by price and type, boasting of excellent choice for every budget and expectations. </p> 
<p><strong>From hostels to luxury hotels, <a href="https://www.safarinow.com/destinations/south-africa/hub.aspx" target=_blank">click here.</strong></a> to check average prices per night.</p> 
</div>

<div>
<h2>Language Tips</h2>
<p>Doesn’t everyone speak English? The answer to that is no. This is why it is important to be prepared when travelling to countries where the majority of the population speaks a different language. A dictionary is useful, and also there are some key phrases to learn that will show respect to the locals and will make getting around slightly easier. </p>
<p>Furthermore, knowing the local etiquette could go a long way in ensuring your stay is pleasurable. For example, avoid conversations about religion, politics, and racism. Also, always communicate face to face as this is important to South Africans.  </p>
<p>South Africa recognises 11 official languages, including Zulu, Xhosa, English, Afrikaans (derived from Dutch), Northern Sotho, Tswana. Less than half of people speak English, being the second most common language after Zulu. White South Africans may also speak other European languages such as Italian, French, Portuguese, German, Greek and French. Indian South Africans may speak Indian languages such as Gujarati, Hindi, and Urdu.</p>
<p>Key phrases in Afrikaans: </p>
<li>Hello – Hallo (hal-low)</li>
<li>Thank you – Dankie (dahn-key)</li>
<li>Please – Asseblief (ah-she-bleef)</li>
<li>Good-bye – Totsiens (tot-seens)</li>
<li>Do you speak English? – Praat jy Engels? (praat yay enn-els)</li>

<div>
<h2>Safety</h2>
<p>The UK government advises that out of over 430,000 British tourists that travel to South Africa each year, only a small number of them encounter problems.  British nationals are targeted for scams, but there are alerts regarding the high level of crime, including theft, rape, and murder. As such, it is best to avoid isolated areas, townships, walking at night, displaying valuable objects. Also, it is best to limit alcohol intake, and never leave drinks unattended.  </p>
<p>As general travel rules, always carry a photo ID with you, know where you are going and how you will get there. If possible, let someone know of your whereabouts if you are going in remote locations. Again, using common sense would help you stay safe and enjoy your journey in a magnificent country that is South Africa. </p>
</div>

